{"type":"message","id":"89e0aa4d","parentId":"6c8fdfcf","timestamp":"2026-04-09T11:45:19.558Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good, product-selector is now in the agents list. But there's another issue - I also need to look at the `bindings` section to make sure product-selector is properly routed. Let me check the bindings.\n\nAlso, looking at the bindings:\n```json\n\"bindings\": [\n  {\"agentId\": \"tts\", \"match\": {\"channel\": \"feishu\", \"accountId\": \"tts\"}},\n  {\"agentId\": \"main\", \"match\": {\"channel\": \"feishu\", \"accountId\": \"kiit\"}}\n]\n```\n\nproduct-selector is not in bindings, so it might be using the default main routing. But since product-selector is spawned as a subagent from main, the binding shouldn't matter for subagent selection - that's controlled by sessions_spawn.\n \nFor product-selector to be spawned via sessions_spawn with runtime \"subagent\", the openclaw.json entry needs to have agentDir pointing to the agent directory. Since the product-selector config.json specifies runtime \"subagent\", the system should read from the proper agent directory when spawning it. But wait - I should verify whether product-selector is actually registered in openclaw.json at all, since that might be what's preventing it from being found as a subagent.\n\nLooking at the config more carefully, product-selector was previously accessed directly via main/product-selector, but the agents list only shows main and tts. The product-selector config at `/home/halei/.openclaw/agents/main/product-selector/agent/config.json` has runtime \"subagent\", which means it should be spawned rather than run directly. This suggests the system might be trying to run it as a regular agent instead of spawning it as a subagent, which would fail if it's not properly registered.\n\nI've already added product-selector to the agents list, so the next step would be restarting the gateway to see if that resolves the issue."},{"type":"