i:default` instead.\n\nActually, let me think about this differently. The openclaw.json has `agents.defaults.model.primary` set to `minimax/MiniMax-M2.7` and `fallbacks: [\"gemini/gemini-1.5-flash\"]`. These are the agent defaults - they're not channel-specific. For the tts agent, I explicitly set `model: \"gemini/gemini-2.0-flash\"` in the agents list, but the session is still getting `minimax:cn` auth profile which forces MiniMax.\n\nThe auth profile binding seems to be auto-detected per-user based on channel identity. The real fix is to ensure the TTS agent's default auth profile for new sessions is `gemini:default` instead of letting it auto-detect to `minimax:cn`. Since the openclaw.json global `agents.defaults.models` has both minimax and gemini with aliases, and tts has `model: \"gemini/gemini-2.0-flash\"` explicitly set, the problem is the `minimax:cn` auth profile being picked up automatically.\n\nThe gateway might be storing per-user channel auth in a different location, and for the user `ou_42b0f5aa88c1415647c200a3dc0a8f68` talking to tts, the system is defaulting to `minimax:cn`. The HALEI user's tts session (with the ou_f590c429... user) was the one I edited, but there's now a new session for a different user that has the minimax binding.\n\nI should change the default auth profile in the openclaw.json to use `gemini:default` instead of the auto-detected `minimax:cn`. The auth.profiles in openclaw.json currently shows `minimax:cn` and `openrouter:default`, so I need to add a `gemini:default` entry there.\n\nBut wait - the tts agent's auth-profiles.json only has `gemini:default`, not `minimax:cn`. So where is the `minimax:cn` binding coming from? It must be coming from a global auth profile. Let me check the full openclaw.json auth section to see where this is actually stored.\n\nActually, I should look at what `agents.defaults.model` controls in openclaw.json. It seems like this might be the key to understanding why a new session keeps getting created with minimax:cn instead of gemini:default, even though I edited the session.\n\nActually, let me just try the simplest fix: check if there's a way to set the default model for the tts agent in openclaw.json's agents list, since setting it in config.json alone didn't work. And also check if there's an agents.defaults section that might be overriding.\n\nI already added `model: \"gemini/gemini-2.0-flash\"` to the tts agent in the openclaw.json agents list. But maybe the issue is that the global agents.defaults.model is being applied to tts instead of the agent-specific one.\n\nLet me just check the current state and try to set it in agents.defaults, or maybe I need to look at how the model selection actually works in openclaw.json - there's a defaults.models section with aliases, so maybe the model string needs to match one of those aliases exactly.\n\nThe simplest fix is probably to change `agents.defaults.model.primary` to `gemini/gemini-2.0-flash` for the tts agent. But I'm not sure if that will work since tts already has an explicit model override.\n\nLet me think about this differently - the real issue might be with the auth profile, not the model itself. The auth profile is binding the session to minimax:cn, which is forcing the model to be MiniMax. So I should fix the auth profile first.\n\nI already set up the tts agent's auth-profiles.json to use gemini:default, but when a new session starts it's still getting minimax:cn. This suggests the global agents.auth.profiles in openclaw.json is being used instead of the agent-specific one.\n\nLet me check if minimax:cn is actually defined in the global auth profiles - if it's not, then where is this binding coming from? I need to trace where the minimax:cn binding is actually being set. I'm realizing the session's `authProfileOverride` is set to `minimax:cn`, but that profile doesn't actually exist in the global auth configuration, which means it must be coming from somewhere else. The tts agent only has `gemini:default` in its auth-profiles.json, yet the session is somehow bound to a non-existent `minimax:cn` profile - this suggests the session binding might be cached or coming from a different source entirely. I'm realizing the `authProfileOverride` might be the key here—if it's set to `minimax:cn` and that profile doesn't actually exist in auth-profiles, then OpenClaw could be falling back to some default behavior. Let me check what's actually in the global auth-profiles to understand why a non-existent profile override is being applied.\n\nLooking at the channel configuration more carefully, I see the channel is feishu with accountId \"tts\", and the delivery context shows `accountId: \"tts\"` with the user ID. I'm wondering if the minimax:cn binding is actually coming from a global default for new sessions rather than from the tts agent's specific configuration.\n\nLet me try the most direct approach: if the new session is defaulting to `minimax:cn` because it's a fresh session without a config.json model set, I should ensure the tts agent's config.json has the model explicitly configured. I already did add `model: \"gemini/gemini-2.0-flash\"` to it, so that should be working. But since a new session was created after restart and it's still using MiniMax, maybe the config.json changes need a full gateway restart to take effect, or the issue is that the session's auth profile is still pointing to minimax.\n\nActually, I need to step back and think about where this `minimax:cn` binding is even coming from. Let me look at the global openclaw.json auth profiles section to see if that's where the session is pulling the minimax:cn from.\n\nWait, I think I see it now. The channel config has `accountId: \"tts\"` in the delivery context, and there's a global feishu account config for \"tts\". So when a new session starts for that channel, it's binding to the \"tts\" account which might have its own default auth profile. I should check if the feishu account-level config has any default auth bindings that would override what I've set.\n\nBut actually, the session's `authProfileOverride: \"minimax:cn\"` is the real problem here - it's forcing that auth profile even though I've configured `gemini:default` in the auth-profiles. The simplest fix would be to add `minimax:cn` to the global auth-profiles but point it to gemini instead, so when that override is applied it uses the right profile. Or I could check the feishu account config to see if there's a default auth profile setting I can change there."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_fzrny8cta4p2_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat /home/halei/.openclaw/openclaw.json | python3 -c \"\nimport json, sys\nd = json.load(sys.stdin)\n# Find auth profiles\nauth = d.get('auth', {})\nprint('auth:', json.dumps(auth, indent=2))\n# Find channel feishu accounts for any default auth binding\nchannels = d.get('channels', {})\nfor ch_name, ch in channels.items():\n    accounts = ch.get('accounts', {})\n    for acc_id, acc in accounts.items():\n        if any(k for k in acc.keys() if 'auth' in k.lower() or 'profile' in k.lower()):\n            print(f'Channel {ch_name}, account {acc_id}:', json.dumps(acc))\n\""}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775738096154,"responseId":"0626cff01a85bacb680c276e96544e23"}}
